FacultyAbolishes Comp Requirement
By a vote of 62-14, the faculty
Monday published the longstanding general graduation requirement that seniors must
pass a comprehensive examination in their major field of
study. In doing so, the faculty
also voted to allow individual
departments to institute alberta
time programs such as seminars
or research projects. to replace
the old requirement.
However, it motors are required to pass the departmental
programs in order to graduate.
the new requirements must
have the recommendation of the
dimensional Educational Policy
Committee (EPC) and the approval oi the Faculty Executive
Council.
Students presently enrolled
may choose to satisfy either
new mandatory departmental
programs or the old comprehensive examination requirement.
The faculty after on the mo»
tion after extended debate on
the matter at its Oct. 27 meets
ing. Monday's debate was devoted to minor changes in working of an amendment offered by
Asst. Prof. John H. harley
(Philosophy) that will allow for
the departmental replacement
of the comp requirement.
However, before the secret
ballot vote was taken, Prol.
John R. Kleinschmidt (French),
chairman of the faculty, authorized the pro and con arguments regarding comes by reading from the minutes of the Executive Council meeting at
which comes were discussed.
The Executive Council last
month divided events on the
comp issue, with time members
favorite evolution and live others opposed.
Numerous departments this
week began preliminary discuss
lions about the possibility of es—
publishing replacement pro
grams for seniors presently enrolled.
The text of the approved
motion on comes:
“The college requirement
that seniors must take and
pass a comprehensive examination in their major field be
published, effective for the
class of 1970.
“Any department may replace the present college grad
nation requirement by institub
ing a program which is pain
of its course structure or in addition to its course structure.
Such a program could consist
of a comprehensive examination, a thesis or paper, a particular course or seminar, 3
research project, a public performance, or any combination
of these. These programs may
be either optional or required
within a major ﬁend, but it
passing the departmental program is required for graduation in that major field, then
such a program must be re«
posted with recommendation
by the additional EPC to the
Executive Council and our
proved by that body.
“As such a requirement
within a major field is not a
new requirement, but a replacement for the present college graduation requirements,
all students now enrolled in
the college who choose to mail- in those departments which
adopt mandatory programs,
will have the option of satisfying the departmental program
or passing the present form of
comprehensive examination.”
