luegrass Singer there Saturday Night
By Ron Stanford
Direct from the Grand Ole
Opry of Nashville, all] Monv
too and the Bluegrass Boys
will be in Grinnell’s South
Lounge tomorrow night at 9
pin. Monroe, who has been a
top attraction in the Grand
Ole opry since 1939. is widely
recognized as the originally
of bluegrass music.
Throughout the agencies and
theories the music which later
cyclverl into bluegrass was
known as “string band bus
sic,” usually played with a
guitar, middle, ‘and banks.
Monrcc started playing protcssionally in the early 1930’s
with his brothers charles and
march. In 1938, he split with
his brother charles and formed the now famous Bluegrass
Boys
Monroe developed a completely new style oi music that
incorporated the traditional
music oi the string band and
a more driving sound, the
lead being taken by the middle,
banks, and mongolia. The
mongolia is Monroe‘s insert»
ment. By the early 1940’s the
world of country music had
adopted the term bluegrass
music from the name at Mon
joe’s group.
Bill Monroe's band has been
considered the training ground
for many a country music
star. Perhaps the most famous
musicians who performed with
Monroe were center plant and
Earl Scruggs. it was during
his stay with the Bluegrass
Boys that Earl Scruggs deVeloped his unique style of
banks finger-picking. Other
potatoes who have performed
with Monroe include Don
Reno, back sitemap, Bill
Keith, and Del McCourry.
Monroe has been one at the
most residential forces in country music. When the import
dance of string band music be
can to want as electricity
country music gained pupils
larity, Monroe gave a new life
to unamplliied string band
music.
Monroe has remained true to
his musical principles through
out his career and has con
oriented an incredible number
oi musical competitions.
Among his best known works
are “Footprints in the Snow,“
“1 Hear 3 Sweet Voice calls
inst" "Uncle Pen,” “Roar
note," and the “Blue Moon at
Kentucky.”
Monroe, born in Rosene,
Kentucky, attributes the ideas
for his music to many sources.
The song “Uncle Pen,” for example, was written in memory or his fiddlerplaying uncle
who ﬁrss taught him the try-
national mountain middle tunes.
Monroe also learned much
from Arnold Schultz, a black
guitarist who played at cancer
in the Rosene area.
The importance of Monroe’s
music has been recognized by
many. This summer both the
State of Kentucky and the
Smithsonian institution hundred Monroe for his contribution
to American music.
